## Transformation of Immigration Policy and Border Security

Given that all 19 hijackers entered the U.S. through legal travel channels, immigration policy became heavily influenced by national security concerns:

- **Heightened Screening and Visa Controls:** The government implemented stricter visa vetting and border controls, focusing on preventing terrorists from entering the country ([Migration Policy Institute, 2011](https://www.migrationpolicy.org/article/post-911-policies-dramatically-alter-us-immigration-landscape/)).

- **Information Sharing and Databases:** Vast interoperable databases were created to collect and share information among law enforcement and intelligence agencies, enhancing surveillance capabilities ([Migration Policy Institute, 2011](https://www.migrationpolicy.org/article/post-911-policies-dramatically-alter-us-immigration-landscape/)).

- **Focus on Noncitizens:** Government actions primarily targeted noncitizens, especially unauthorized immigrants, rather than American Muslims or citizens, avoiding mass internment or moratoriums on immigration ([Migration Policy Institute, 2011](https://www.migrationpolicy.org/article/post-911-policies-dramatically-alter-us-immigration-landscape/)).

These changes have reshaped the U.S. immigration system into one dominated by security and border control priorities, significantly impacting immigrant communities and policy debates.

---

## Impact on Civil Liberties and Public Trust

The post-9/11 era has been marked by tension between security measures and civil liberties:

- **Surveillance and Privacy Concerns:** The expansion of government surveillance capabilities has been met with resistance from civil liberties groups, who argue that laws like the Patriot Act infringe on constitutional rights ([New York Times, 2011](https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/07/us/sept-11-reckoning/civil.html)).

- **Public Distrust:** Revelations of abuses and secretive government programs have contributed to growing public skepticism toward American institutions. The challenge remains how to balance national security with protecting individual freedoms and rebuilding trust ([Time, 2021](https://time.com/6096903/september-11-legal-history/)).

- **Racial and Religious Profiling:** Muslim Americans and people perceived to be Muslim have faced increased discrimination and scrutiny, leading to a rise in complaints of abuse and hate crimes ([PBS NewsHour, 2019](https://www.pbs.org/newshour/nation/9-11-to-today-ways-we-have-changed)).

