## Changes in Air Travel and Transportation Security

9/11 fundamentally altered aviation security and travel culture:

| Aspect                  | Pre-9/11                             | Post-9/11 Changes                                  |
|-------------------------|------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------|
| Airport Security        | Minimal screening, no federal TSA  | Creation of TSA; rigorous passenger screening     |
| Identification         | Varied forms accepted               | Mandatory government-issued photo ID for flights  |
| Carry-on Regulations    | Lenient                            | Strict limitations on liquids, electronics, etc. |
| Passenger Experience   | Relatively quick boarding          | Longer wait times, invasive security procedures   |
| Surveillance           | Limited                           | Full-body scanners, behavioral profiling          |

While these measures have arguably made air travel safer, they have also increased travel time and raised privacy concerns, especially among minority travelers ([KQED, 2014](https://www.kqed.org/lowdown/14066/13-years-later-four-major-lasting-impacts-of-911)).

