## Conclusion and Opinion

The legacy of 9/11 is complex and multifaceted. It undeniably made America safer from large-scale terrorist attacks on its soil, as evidenced by the absence of attacks comparable to 9/11 since then ([History.com, 2021](https://www.history.com/news/september-11-changes-america)). However, this increased security came at significant costs: the expansion of government surveillance and executive power has challenged civil liberties and privacy; prolonged military engagements have strained resources and sparked debate over their efficacy; and societal divisions have deepened, particularly affecting Muslim and immigrant communities.

In my assessment, while the security imperatives post-9/11 were necessary to address unprecedented threats, the approach often lacked sufficient safeguards against overreach. The balance between protecting citizens and preserving constitutional freedoms remains delicate and unresolved. Moving forward, recalibrating this balance with transparent oversight and renewed public trust is essential to uphold both security and democratic values ([Time, 2021](https://time.com/6096903/september-11-legal-history/)).

